==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /a:r/

===Etymology 1===
From Germanic ''*aizo''.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[era|ēra]] (Dutch [[eer]]), Old High German [[era|ēra]] (German [[Ehre]]), Old Norse [[eir]].

====Noun====
'''ār''' ''[[Wiktionary Appendix:Old English strong declension|strong]] f''
# [[honor]], [[glory]], [[grace]]
#:''He sundor lif wæs foreberende eallum ðam arum'': he preferred a private life to all honours.

===Etymology 2===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Norse [[ár]].

====Noun====
'''ār''' ''f''
# an [[oar]]

===Etymology 3===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Saxon [[eru|ēru]], Old Norse [[árr]], Gothic [[𐌰𐌹𐍂𐌿𐍃]].

====Noun====
'''ār''' ''m''
# a [[messenger]] or [[herald]]; an [[angel]]; a [[missionary]]

